                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">There are LONG and involved threads on another post that went down the trail of discussing test.  The post started out as a discussion of the new changes, and got into a discussion on test and test practices.  If possible, I'd like to pull the 'test and test practices' discussion into a seperate thread, this one.
<br />

<br />
Background: In real life I work in test.  I'm an electrical engineer who has done systems related computer test for 8 years now.  I've at least been exposed to programming (though I will NOT claim to be a programmer).  In my social life, I've gamed since the early '70s, starting with "Melee", "Wizard" and "Death Test" as well as the original D&D and SPI games War of the Rings gamette, Gondor.  Long and short is I've got over 30 years of game experience including working for a shop that did game design (no, I was not a game designer but I worked closely with the designers and was very much clued in on game design and balance issues because of it).  Long and short: I feel VERY qualified to speak to test and test issues and I also feel very qualified to talk about game design issues.
<br />

<br />
Let me make something very clear here: I do NOT work for SOE or Verant (I'll say "EQ" in this context to save typing from here on out) or any gaming company at this point in time.  I have never worked for EQ and likely never will (save in the form of being an outspoken player).
<br />

<br />
First point:
<br />

<br />
Test is not an exact science.  Test changes with the product being tested.  When testing a program, you will need to take different considerations and expertise than when testing a piece of hardware.  In ways, the hardware is easier, since it has defined capabilities.  Softwares capabilities are often subtle and might act in unintended ways because of interactivity issues with both other programs and with hardware.  These unintended actions will be termed "bugs" or "features" depending on the general consensus of their utility.
<br />

<br />
In order to focus on one issue in test, we will, should, try to elliminate other issues that might cause confusion and to have a "grounding" to start from.
<br />

<br />
For example, if I were doing test in EQ, I would use the following pattern ALWAYS to test a zone under development:
<br />

<br />
1) Test the new zone "live" without any critters.  Just have a set of players walk the zone.  This would be after the maps have been drawn and implemented, of course, so it does imply that there has been a basic test of the rendering of the map prior to this.  These players would test the map and make sure that the geography doesn't cause problems.  There should be NO objects in zone save those that deal with the map.  This level of test would include testing zoning in and out.
<br />

<br />
2) Once you are confident you have the basic geography down, let the players duel and test how combat works in that zone.  Does Line of Sight "LoS" function as expected?  How about range?  Basically, they test the basic physics of the zone.
<br />

<br />
3) Once you are confident that the physics work, add creatures.  Initially, have no players in zone, just creatures.  Observe their behaviour (assuming they have any) and note any problems inherent with that behaviour.
<br />

<br />
4) Now allow players to be involved with the zone inhabitants.  This test could further be broken down by having a non-combatant test with none of the aggressive mobs in zone and have folks walk through quest interaction (for example) and subsequently test combatants alone.  Finally, test the zone with both combatants and non-combants active at the same time.
<br />

<br />
Now, these tests, idealy, will be done in house and prior to releasing the proposed zone to the test server.  This should be ond as "Whit Box" testing, in which the tester is very familiar with the inner workings of the code and thus knows what to test.  Unfortunately, a white box tester also knows what to avoid and may well walk passed a problem in her/his code without even thinking they are doing so.
<br />

<br />
The next phase of testing:
<br />

<br />
5) Open the zone up live on a semipublic server to allow the masses a chance at the zone and see what they can find on their own.  This is called "Black Box" testing since the "public" doesn't really know how the code was created and thus interfaces purely in an intuitive fashion using the program, the zone, in fashions that seem appropriate to them at the time, versus what was designed as "appropriate."
<br />

<br />
For a good test, both forms of test must be performed.  Unfortunately, it requires time and resources to make this kind of testing commitment, and we have proven to the development community that we are perfectly willing to by a new game or product despite how well it has been tested... as long as the hype is good.  Hype sells games first, quality will keep the game selling but if you make a profit off of the initial pulse from hype, what do you care about subsequent sales when you are off to the new project?
<br />

<br />
Now, what's happening on the test server is indicative of a team that does not understand or care about test.  Rather than doing a preliminary in house test under controlled conditions, or white box test, they are doing public testing of code that is not, quite, yet ready for black box testing.  A good in house test could do things like arrange for mob A to be available so that a mock raiding force can go after it.  Said mock force being made available from dedicated in house testers.  This is because they can literally set up a test server with just the one zone and nothing else... thus limiting interactions and issues of bandwitdth caused by other zones.  This is not practical on a "live" public server because you have to trust that you can get enough folks to sign on during the hours your sys admin and dev team is available to rig up the spot test, which just isn't practical.  Works best if you are working with folks you KNOW will be there because they work at your office 9-5.  Now, IF this form of testing were done in house, prior to sending the code to the public servers, the black box testing, on the public servers, would be much more stable and much more productive at ironing out odd bugs that a finite team of developers are unlikely to think of trying.
<br />

<br />
Another unfortunate factor is that good testers don't sell copies of games like good hype does.  Thus, you have companies choosing beta testers based on factors other than their ability to test.  Sony made this type of choice when they decided to choose from their Legends players for Beta test of EQ2 versus seeking out a good test crew from all walks of life.  It is key to good test that you choose folks from all facets of your audience, trained and untrained, casual and serious.  Until you do this, you will get a skewed test.  Evidence is that Sony always chooses one set of folks for test: 65s.  Which is fine, if you always issue a 65th level character to all new players.  Unfortunately, the reality is that folks start at level one and are immediatly hit with some odd situations: 14th level spells that are attainable only by purchase through LDoN points, and only with so many points that you will likely be 35th level before you can buy them is just one example.
<br />

<br />
Long and short: there is a test methodology out there.  The test server has a role in this methodology but it should be late in test.  Unfortunately, companies have found that folks will be their beta testers and have started selling products that are, in effect, beta level code.  First we must insist on good solid test practices.  Second we must back up that claim with action by refusing to by code that has not been thoroughly tested.  Third, we must take our part by giving feedback for those issues that we do note and by broadcasting those problems so that folks can make informed decisions when buying products.  This is because if there are a LOT of complaints about the quality of a companies product, or a developers product, we, the buyers, can make an informed decision to take our dollars elsewhere.
<br />

<br />
Please add to this and debate what I've said.  This is a BIG subject so I'm sure I've missed a few nuances.  I tried not to go into too much detail because I wanted to discuss methodology more than specific EQ cases (which might well mean this should be on a different forum).
<br />

<br />
And most importantly... thanks for having the patience to get this far in a rambling post.  <img src="images/smiles/icon_smile.gif" alt="icon_smile.gif" border="0" /></span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br />GnarliAnna
<br />
64 Enchanter of Silent Watchers
<br />
Cazic-Thule</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
