                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Yes, I agree with everything you say. Thanks for the very good summary.
<br />

<br />
I have posted about test server in the past on other boards. About how it works (player perspective), what goes on there and why. It is interesting, since it can have such a big impact on your life as a consumer. You can see it exists, but not understand it because its a bit of an odd beast. I also have no affiliation at all with SOE or Verant or any of that. Just a guess based on what I see.
<br />

<br />
A few extra things I would like to add (EQ specific):
<br />

<br />
* Typically there is testing performed immediately by the programmers. That tests the new or changed code as an entity on its own. 
<br />
* Then it gets added to a larger test set; usually in house as you say. SOE must have one of these (although they never mention it), since they are able to create, test, and release a new zone to Legends before releasing it to Test.
<br />
* There is a server dedicated to testing of expansions via public beta.
<br />
* Test Server, which is the last place testing goes on before it goes to production. During the development/beta of an expansion, the code on Test server is a bridge between what was and what will be. During LDoN, for example, Test Server had the new database added although we didn't have access to the items or the zones. On the Beta server, they had access to both. Whats more, there is often a secondary set of changes being made and tested completely separately of the expansion code/database. So, Test looks fairly confusing for a while, as you see bits and pieces of separate projects. While GoD was being tested, Test server had a subset of those changes (ie DX9 was to go in much early than it eventually did) plus it also had the "normal" upgrades to general Everquest. For example the melee changes and testing, and the tradeskilling UI upgrade.
<br />

<br />
The issue I see is that it feels like the layer between the programmers desk, and the Test Server is much thinner than all this indicates. In other words comparitively little is tested before it goes to Test Server. By "comparitively little" I refer to the daily updates and not the large enchancements/expansions. We get a big lump of new code, such as DX9, new targeting system, and new collision system. That had substantial testing before it came to Test server; although it was not perfect. After that we get a whole slew of little patches. Some of those are good and some are not (they undo things that had previously been fixed).
<br />

<br />
That does not mean that I think they tested DX9 very little inhouse before it went to test. Actually - they obviously were well under way with that upgrade before we saw it on test. But, once that was done there seemed to be so many small updates that have issues. The collision system felt like it could have used another month of work before it even appeared on Test Server. DX9, that portion I think needed to go out early since the variation of the hardware people run has a direct impact on the amount of testing time required.
<br />

<br />
Collision testing though seemed to fail substantially; and it is independent of the client hardware. The tuning of it took a long time. So why was it released at the same time as the DX9 changes? Probably because they have a common subset of code. Collisions (interaction with the world, dropping through holes, mobs getting stuck etc), Targeting of moving items, line of sight issues, and DX9 are all probably fundamentally linked. But, they also probably evolved separately and the DX9 graphics needed to go out for testing, which in turn pulls the other "not so ready" pieces along. That's a total guess, but it seems reasonable. Then, Test server deals with the issues that arise from several different items at varying stages of readiness. And, February/March of this year were very bumpy months on test server.
<br />

<br />
One last point is that the project timeline often has a large say on when code is "done". We don't see what other projects are held up by this one sliding. We also don't always see other issues such as April Fools day; one that can be expensive for SOE since they deal with the fallout of "practical jokes" and the people who didn't get it. They may not get it since its not April 1st when they read it, and they read only a portion and not the "Surprise!!" that originally was part of the post.
<br />

<br />
So, SOE may very well have a policy of not adding fuel to that fire by releasing an update for a week before or a week after, some such thing. In that case, the effect of a sliding release date can be substantial. They take the best guess at the status of the code and what that will do when it is put into production, vs other factors in the hopper that are jsut as real to them (though not at all obvious to the players).
<br />

<br />
There! Hopefully some of the productive/positive conversation people asked to hear about on the other thread.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"><br /><br />Last edited by Trellium on Thu Apr 01, 2004 6:48 pm; edited 6 times in total</span></td>
