                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">The single biggest issue I see is that of limited test.  Specifically, they limit the 'audience' of testers and don't get a well rounded test out of it.  I'm not talking specifically to the test server here but to the game industry in general... however, EQ is unfortunately a glaring example because all of the recent expansions have obviously been aimed at high levels.  Don't get me wrong, high levels are people too and need things to do... but, people who are just starting the game (yes, there are real newbs out there) should be able to enjoy the content at all levels and there are great dissinsentives to that:
<br />

<br />
A) The chest opening spells start at level 14, but, you can't get into adventures to buy these spells until 20.  Serious continuity flaw here.
<br />
B) The chest opening spells require enough points to buy (for level 14) that you can't buy them until (and I'm guessing) approximately level 35... not at 1 point per adventure in the 20s.
<br />
C) LDoN RAIDS were for average 63 and up... do ya think lower levels woulda liked to raid?
<br />

<br />
Fact is most of the expansions have been geared to higher levels, which again is ok, but, the content was not tested against all levels... only those at high levels.  If it had been tested at all levels, continuity problems like those above would not exist.  Part of white box testing, is to go to known stress points and test them out.  In the case of LDoN, this means you go to the lowest level of content, and give it a test drive and you also go to the highest level of the content and test drive it.  It's obvious to me that they only test drove it at the upper end.</span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br />GnarliAnna
<br />
64 Enchanter of Silent Watchers
<br />
Cazic-Thule</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
