                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I agree the LDoN raids are poorly made and balanced... not from direct experience but from a universal agreement of all the posts I've read on the LDoN raids.
<br />

<br />
However, the fact is that the raid content was obviously geared to folks who satisfied certain criteria:
<br />

<br />
A) High level... 63 was the average just to get in the door... 65 is really required
<br />
B) Best gear... only time geared guilds stand a chance here based on everything I've read.
<br />

<br />
Think about it: LDoN has been heralded as the best expansion for casual players and yet the best of the content is reserved for high levels who are wearing Time gear.  Add to that the fact that the best augments go ONLY in Time dropped gear and you have a goodly portion of the expansions design focus on... high level content.
<br />

<br />
I can tell you that if the Raid content were well balanced, and doable at all levels that I'd've been doing raids in LDoN from day one... well, close... I'd've been doing them from when I first had the other entrance criteria.  I submit as evidence of this the fact that we had to explain to several folks that raids could only be done with 3 groups averaging 63, that our several groups of 20s, 30s, 40s, 50s, and 60s didn't cut the mustard.
<br />

<br />
You say that there is a lot of low level content and I agree.  It's also not used the way it once was.  Why?  Think about this: with PoP, another high level expansion, we got stones that abbreviated much of that low level content out of existance.  With Luclin we got zones that were so high on exp bonus, that there was literally no reason to leave these few zones until you were in your 50s.  With Vellius and Kunark, the content reached all the way down to 35th level.  Point being that the incentive is to level as fast as possible to be able to explore the content.  How does this relate to test?  If they'd tested the content at all levels, they would've realized the significant holes they left in their content for lower levels.  They might also have realised flaws in their code.  Anyone remember the fear kiting exploit in OT?  If they'd tested the Kunark content at all available levels, odds on they would've run across an exping group that figured this one out.  Seems to me they restricted their testing to the content that was particular.  Ie: testing out the Epic quests, and singular mobs, rather than simple exp type encounters.
<br />

<br />
Wow, this is sounding like I'm high level bashing and that is NOT my intent.  High levels need content too.  But, the game would be much more healthy if the whole game were well tested rather than one aspect of the game.  The point of my diatribe is that we are only testing the high end of the game... which means we are NOT being careful to test all aspects, or as many as we reasonably can, of the game.  Which means our testing is flawed, skewed and inadequate.  Which leads us to problems like we have now with EQ.
<br />

<br />
Back to square one: the test community needs to span a wide variety of levels, the players a wide variety of play styles and include folks not of the intended audience, if possible.  Why?  Because you can't guarantee that only those of the intended audience will find an interest in the product in question.</span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br />GnarliAnna
<br />
64 Enchanter of Silent Watchers
<br />
Cazic-Thule</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
